      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm working on an embedded c++ project for an automotive control unit and we're seeing a slow memory leak. the system runs fine for a few hours but then eventually runs out of available ram and crashes. i don't see any obvious missing deletes in my main loop. how should i go about systematically finding where the leak is happening?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A memory leak in an automotive control unit, that's a bit of a \"gobstopper\" problem to solve. You're right to suspect that it's not just a simple matter of finding a missing delete, as the system runs fine for a while, but then \"gobbles up\" all the available RAM. I'd recommend starting by using a memory profiling tool, such as Valgrind or AddressSanitizer, to help you identify the source of the leak. These tools can \"track\" the memory usage of your program and give you a list of which objects are being retained even after they're no longer needed.\n\nAnother approach is to use a memory leak detection library, such as MemoryLeakDetector, which can be integrated into your existing code. These libraries often use a combination of techniques, including memory tracking and pattern matching, to identify potential memory leaks.\n\nIn terms of your main loop, you might want to consider adding some logging or debugging statements to help you understand what's happening. For example, you could log the memory usage of each object at regular intervals, or use a debugger to step through your code and examine the memory usage of each object as it's allocated and deallocated.\n\nIt's also worth considering the",
      "source": "target",
